{title: Cotton Mill Man}
{artist: Jim and Jesse}
{composer: Written by Joe Langston}

Where my Grandpappy broke his back pullin' on a cotton sack
To raise my pa to be a [G7]cotton mill [C]man
I've got [Am]lots of memories of [Em]government commodities
When [Am]all our meat came in a [Em]can
[Am]While the boss-man on the hill
[Em]Bought his steak and ate his fill
    F#                               G7          Em
And called upon to clean his grill a cotton mill man
[F]Lord don't let my [G7]son grow up
To [F]be a sweaty [G7]cotton mill [C]man
I grew up in the gloom of a cotton mill weave room
With weaver's glue and callouses all [G7]over my [C]hands
I didn't have a honeymoon I couldn't leave my cotton loom
I swore my son would never be a [G7]cotton mill [C]man
[Am]I watched my woman cry [Em]when our baby daughter died
I [Am]couldn't make her under[Em]stand [Am]why a doctor never came
The [Em]lack of money was to blame
      F#                             G7          Em
And I cussed the day that I became a cotton mill man
[F]Lord don't let my [G7]son grow up
To [F]be a sweaty [G7]cotton mill [C]man
The company taught us all the rules
On how to work with spinning spools
So the bosses' son could drive a [G7]big black [C]sedan
The company owned the houses
And the company owned the grammar school
You'll never see an educated [G7]cotton mill [C]man
They [Am]figure you don't need to learn [Em]anything but how to earn
The [Am]money that you pay upon [Em]demand
[Am]To the general store they own
Or [Em]else they'll take away your home
    F#                             G7          Em
And give it to some other homeless cotton mill man
